SIMPLE: muse
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Muse
<hw>Muse</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From F.
<ets>musse</ets>. See <er>Muset</er>.]</ety> <def>A gap or hole in a
hedge, hence, wall, or the like, through which a wild animal is
accustomed to pass; a muset.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Find a hare without a <qex>muse</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Old
Prov.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muse</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Muse
<hw>Muse</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>Muse</ets>, L.
<ets>Musa</ets>, Gr. <?/. Cf. <er>Mosaic</er>, <pos>n.</pos>,
<er>Music</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Class. Myth.)</fld> <def>One of
the nine goddesses, daughters of Zeus and Mnemosyne, who presided over
song and the different kinds of poetry, and also the arts and sciences;
-- often used in the plural. At one time certain other goddesses were
considered as muses.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Granville commands; your aid, O Muses, bring:⟦br⟧
What <qex>Muse</qex> for Granville can refuse to sing?</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The names of the Muses and the arts they presided over
were: <examp>Calliope</examp> (Epic poetry), <examp>Clio</examp>
(History), <examp>Erato</examp> (Lyric poetry), <examp>Euterpe</examp>
(music), <examp>Melpomene</examp> (Tragedy), <examp>Polymnia</examp> or
<examp>Polyhymnia</examp> (religious music), <examp>Terpsichore</examp>
(dance), <examp>Thalia</examp> (comedy), and <examp>Urania</examp>
(astronomy).</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A particular power and practice of poetry; the
inspirational genius of a poet.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A poet; a bard.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muse</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Muse
<hw>Muse</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Mused</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Musing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>muser</ets> to loiter or
trifle, orig., to stand with open mouth, fr. LL. <ets>musus</ets>,
<ets>morsus</ets>, muzzle, snout, fr. L. <ets>morsus</ets> a biting,
bite, fr. <ets>mordere</ets> to bite. See <er>Morsel</er>, and cf.
<er>Amuse</er>, <er>Muzzle</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To think closely; to study in silence; to meditate.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧Thereon <xex>mused</xex> he.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>mused</qex> upon some dangerous plot.</q> <rj><qau>Sir P.
Sidney.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To be absent in mind; to be so occupied in study or
contemplation as not to observe passing scenes or things present; to be
in a brown study.</def> <rj><au>Daniel.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To wonder.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Spenser.</au> <au>B. Jonson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To consider; meditate; ruminate. See
<er>Ponder</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muse</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Muse
<hw>Muse</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To think on; to
meditate on.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Come, then, expressive Silence, <qex>muse</qex> his praise.</q>
<rj><qau>Thomson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To wonder at.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muse</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Muse
<hw>Muse</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Contemplation which
abstracts the mind from passing scenes; absorbing thought; hence,
absence of mind; a brown study.</def> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Wonder, or admiration.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Museful</ent>⟦br⟧
